<answer>Let $(\rho, \theta, \phi)$ be the spherical coordinates of the point with rectangular coordinates $(x, y, -z).$ Then, we have:
\begin{align*}
x &= \rho  \cos \phi  \sin \theta \\
y &= \rho  \sin \phi  \sin \theta \\
z &= -\rho  \cos \phi
\end{align*}
Solving for $\rho, \theta, \phi$ in terms of $x, y, z$, we get:
\begin{align*}
\rho &= \sqrt{x^2 + y^2 + z^2} \\
\theta &= \tan^{-1} \left(\frac{y}{x}\right) \\
\phi &= \cos^{-1} \left(\frac{z}{\rho}\right)
\end{align*}
Substituting $z = -\rho  \cos \phi$ into the equation for $\phi$, we get:
\begin{align*}
\phi &= \cos^{-1} \left(-\cos^2 \phi\right) \\
\phi &= \frac{\pi}{2}
\end{align*}
Substituting $x = -y$ into the equation for $\theta$, we get:
\begin{align*}
\theta &= \tan^{-1} \left(\frac{y}{-y}\right) \\
\theta &= \frac{3\pi}{4}
\end{align*}
Substituting $z = -\rho  \cos \phi$ into the equation for $\rho$, we get:
\begin{align*}
\rho &= \sqrt{x^2 + y^2 + (-\rho  \cos \phi)^2} \\
\rho &= \sqrt{2}
\end{align*}
Therefore, the spherical coordinates of the point with rectangular coordinates $(x, y, -z)$ are $(\sqrt{2}, \frac{3\pi}{4}, \frac{\pi}{2}).$
